Review: Damn, I enjoyed this WAY more than I thought I would.  Usually period romances aren’t my thing, but this was great! Loved the subtle drama and the just general vibe of the film, in no small part to the performances by the leads - shoutout Emory-FUCKIN-Cohen, most underrated actor in the game - that just make this…good. It’s a good movie, and I enjoyed it, sometimes that’s all you can ask from a film
I have no mouth, but I must yawn at how FUCKIN bad this was, Jesus Christ.
Not great. The original set a high bar, but this doesn’t even come close. Disappointing, ham fisted, and flat.

Another important piece of art that needs to be shared - this woman is an international treasure and her mission is probably one of the most important causes I can think of in the current era. We don’t consider European indigenous groups when discussing how global governing bodies handle these things because “Europe” is so conflated with “Whiteness” but in Denmark and Sweden and other Scandinavian countries there are indigenous (read, non-white) peoples who are actively oppressed and NEED a permanent forum. These legacies must be preserved. Simple.
Sometimes the world is better off because a piece of art has been put into it. This is one of those times. Glad I got to see it and attend a Q&A with the director.

Watching this movie with a new set of eyes (for lack of a better term) after the last time I watched it has kind of just further cemented how great of a film it is. It’s funny, very punchy, and the characters have a rapport that really has never been recreated since this era of movies ended.But what I noticed more in this watch is the kind of quiet sadness that permeates literally everything. Nobody is “happy” - all…

I was the youngest person in the theater by at least a decade and a half, but goddamn, What a BANGER - incredible needle drops (gotta shout out my tattoo artist Nick for playing the hits from this film on his radio show last month, great tribute) and such a simple yet well executed concept. I can see how this is the point from which a lot of films and genres stem from, and I’d be curious to know the indomitable Bob Thompsons thoughts on it, just as a companion to something like Animal House.

Watched in 3D.This film is one of the most faithful adaptations, and it does everything so fucking well. GOD, What a GREAT fucking movie. Sound, visuals, performances, music, VFX, practical effects, just a great adaptation. There’s nothing I can say that hasn’t already been said, but holy shit. It holds up SO wellAlso, a funny story. I read a lot of Michael Crichton as a kid. Why? Cause a girl I had a crush on in middle school…
Words cannot describe how well-made I think this film is. Seeing it on the big screen. Holy shit. The music. Holy shit. Just everything, I love it

What a weird film, goddamn. I forgot how fuckin…French the French can be sometimes. I kinda love it though, Carax just takes the bonkers and makes it more bonkers somehow - I cannot IMAGINE what the script for this must’ve looked like, it’s so disorientating. One man wearing many hats, smoking many cigarettes, having seemingly many, MANY lives, but are there consequences? Are they even real? I have no idea.
